,Not Recommended,241560,19881860,"Posted: 23 December, 2015",all,FistaCuffLinks,"If you get TL;DR syndrome then skip down to ""Verdict of The Crew"" but I encourage you to read the specifics so that you can accurately judge if this game is right for you.First Rule of The Crew:- DoNOTbuy this game unless you have a human companion to play it with! As many others have probably stated, hardly anybody plays this game online; the servers are ghost towns. The players that are online in this game, based on their driving style, are probably around 10-13 years of age (offense only mildly intended if you are of that age range). It is not uncommon for an online driver to see your car and immediately attempt a T-bone maneuver. Therefore, if you are seriously considering purchasing this game, make absolutely sure that you have a friend to play with online so that this game can begin to live up to the expectations we all had of it.Premise of The Crew:- The Crew was designed to be an MMORG (Massively Multiplayer Online Racing Game), which in concept is absolutely brilliant! In execution, however, The Crew has fallen short due to empty servers and a bug-laden open world. It cannot be denied that the premise of this game is one of the best of all time, but it seems that the makers of The Crew lacked the man-power in their programming teams to make this work well.Accolades of The Crew:- The Crew is one of the most fun games I have ever played! My friend and I would meet online regularly to do missions together, rank up our cars together, take on challenges together and our favorite - drive in the open world together. In terms of sheer enjoyment for a racing video game, The Crew has to make the Top 5! (...when it's working...)- The Crew has amassiveopen world map! The map is probably about a 20:1 scale map of the United States; the map is by no means cartographically accurate, but the major landmarks and cities are there. Everything is down in scale (similar to Midnight Club: LA or the GTA games), but that doesn't mean that the world doesn't feel humongous! It is a daunting task to think about driving from Miami to Seattle, or LA to Niagara Falls, but as one who has done it, there are few things more exciting! There are many little easter eggs on the map to find in addition to the hidden objects and challenges that make simply driving around in the open world interesting and fun.- The Crew has a fairly large list of cars that are available in the game and all of the cars available look great in the game. You can customize your car with different body sets, colors and stickers to make your vehicle one of a kind. The cars also handle pretty well all things considered; The Crew is definitely not a simulator when it comes to driving but for an arcade style racer the car handling is more realistic than it could have been. It should be said that by the time you beat the game and level up your first car to Level 50 parts and a 1200+ rating, however, youwillhave a favorite car or two and for the most part only drive those cars.- The Crew has pretty decent graphics too. I have found myself taking screenshots of the scenery, much like I do with Skyrim, because the world really does look great! Of course, the world looks better at 60-80mph than it does at 180-200mph, even with the best GPUs, but that's to be expected.Complications with The Crew:- This game is buggy. There is no simpler way to say it. And there is no denying it. My friend and I have constantly been thwarted by programming issues within the game. During open world travels we will inevitably come across at least a major bug or two every 30-60 mins. Some of the worst, especially since the new expansion has come out, include (1) infinite loading screens, (2) game freezing during fast travel, and my personal nemesis - (3) the road/world disappearing in front of you [this bug has an relatively easy fix - just open up the map and quickly exit out again, but it is annoying nonetheless. It is also potentially game breaking when you are in a mission or co-op event when the open world map is not accessible.] There is no way to enjoy The Crew without experiencing bugs. Maybe if there were more people online the makers of The Crew would be inclined to fix them, but since there are not, you just have to deal with them. This creates a Love/Hate relationship with this game.- The AI in this game is... wonky, to say the least. For missions/co-op events or in police chases, the AI seems counter-productive (as opposed to challenging) and even vengeful at times. Rubberbandingdefinitelyoccurs in these types of events and should be expected (heck, sometimes I think they designed it that way just so that youNEEDa crew playing with you). In the open world, expect AI driven cars to suddenly swerve in front of you, especially if you are going 200+mph. If there were any corners cut in the programming of this game, I would think that they were cut in this AI department.- If you do end up convincing a friend to buy this game with you so that you can play it together, then you should also know that forming a crew in the game can be difficult at times too. It is normal for my friend and I to spend 15-30 mins trying to get into a crew together and forcing the game to put us on the same server. Game restarts should be expected, and it should also be noted that The Crew doesn't always play nice with Steam's voice chat (probably because it's a Ubisoft game and uses UPlay. **As a side note though, I have not had as many issues with Uplay as I have had with other games they put out**).Tips for The Crew:- Many others have said it on forums and discussion boards, but this gameNEEDSa multiple waypoint system. The gigantic map is just begging for one! It is very frustrating to try and create driving routes and races with your crew/friend with only one waypoint to lay down. Honestly, I am very surprised by this huge oversight!-  Along with that, this game would be vastly improved if there was a community based Player Created Races/Challenges feature. Since open world driving is the best (and most advertised) feature in the game, having a community of racers all creating their own races/routes/challenges would add content and excitement to the game.Verdict of The Crew:- I have put over 80 hours into this game and about 70 of those hours have been genuinely enjoyable! Open world driving is by far my favorite activity and with the help of my friend I have come up with several fantastic driving routes that are always a blast to drive! There is no other game quite like The Crew and my heart wants everyone to buy and enjoy this game.- The remaining 10 hours I have spent in this game, however, make it so that I cannot, in good conscience, recommend this game for the $30/$40 listing price. Even on sale, if youdon'thave a friend to play this game with, I wouldhighlyrecommend that you stay far, far away! But if you do have a friend to play with, I would want you to seriously consider the issues presented in this review and weigh them against your desire for this game:(1) If there is any hesitation, then spend your money elsewhere.(2) If there is still excitement and a ""devil-may-care"" attitude, then all I can say is, ""Good luck!"""
