,Recommended,241560,18298465,"Posted: 2 October, 2015",all,Toxic Fuel,"I followed this game for quite a while before it came out. I was super psyched for a racing game with car customization in an open world, something Need for Speed had not done for a while at the time. However, I will admit that once it came out, I never really heard anything about it. It seems like I basically forgot. Then, a friend of mine got it and I ended up buying it on sale. Clearly, as you can see from my hours, I really have enjoyed this game. However, it has some quirks to it, and they aren't necessarily good. So, here's what I enjoyed about The Crew, and not so much.PROS:The Open World- I didn't realize just how big the map was until I really got into this game. It has, by far, the largest map out of any racing game I have played. I cannot compare it to FUEL simply because I have not played it, but it is bigger than every NFS game. And best of all? The map isnotrepetitive. You can drive from the swamps of the south to the deserts in the west, and have different scenery and small towns/cities in between. It mainly revolves around 5 major cities, and they are New York, Chicago, Miami, Las Vegas, and L.A. The developers certainly did their homework when it comes to the cities, and I applaud them for it. Even after 260 hours of gameplay, I still see places on the map I have not been, making the open world my favorite part of the game, by far.PvP- I find that the PvP is well done. You play in a lobby with up to 8 players at a time, who all choose exactly what event they want to do, and then the game randomly picks one of them. This includes events with any of the 5 specs. Some events are elimination, others regular races, and others a ""king of the hill"" type game. What's even better is the amount of in-game money you get from PvP. Even if you get last place, you still get nearly just as much money as the person in first, and this can make it enjoyable for anyone that plays. PvP is also one of the best ways to earn money. However, it still does matter what place you get, since therearePvP ranks in the game. The higher you place, the faster you rank up.The Graphics- Towards the end of 2015, a free update brought in new, updated graphics along with a weather system, which also includes slick roads after rain. This is all much better than before. I will admit, it does look more washed out than the previous graphics, but I can honestly go either way. I cannot quite handle the game at max settings, but on high-ultra this game looks very good.Car Selection- You can have (almost) anything, from a LaFerrari, to a Hummer H1 Alpha, to a Dodge Challenger. What I like is that the game has 5 different specs for most cars (some ranging from just 1 spec to all 5), which are Street, Dirt, Performance, Raid, and Circuit. Take, for example, the Challenger. It can have all 5 specs, so if you want to go on dirt roads with one, you hop into the dirt spec Challenger. If you want complete offroading, you go with raid. And if you want to take it to the track or go extremely fast on highways, you get the circuit spec, and so on. What's nice is that you only buy one Challenger, and as you progress through the game, you get it in each spec, so you technically have 5 Challengers.NEUTRAL:The Police- I always enjoy it when there is law enforcement in an open-world racing game. At this point, I think it should be mandatory. The Crew, of course, has police, but they are only decent. Nothing more and nothing less. Unfortunately, this is where Need for Speed does something better than The Crew. During a police chase, even with 5 stars, there will never be any more than 5 police cars at once pursuing you, which by the way, are quite easy to take out. The roadblocks are laughable, since they never use anything other than the cars that are pursuing you to block the road, so you can usually speed right through them, unlike NFS: Most Wanted, which eventually has SWAT trucks that basically force you to take another route. There are also no spike strips. While it still can be fun to get into chases and have a friend taking out cops for you, I believe it could be made significantly harder at 5 stars with the use of bigger vehicles and spike strips.Customization- I'm very thankful that The Crew actually has customization to begin with, but it is really lacking. For one, you cannot choose from any color in the spectrum; you just pick from a preset list of colors. Second, the decals are mostly terrible. I tend to use the same 10-15 decals on most cars, or sometimes not at all, because most of the others are just bad looking and don't seem to fit any vehicle. Granted, that is personal preference, but for someone who has played NFS:Most Wanted and Underground 2, those are far superior in customizing.CONS:Uplay- I think you saw this coming. Uplay is a requirement for The Crew, even if you buy it directly from Steam. Youmustdownload Uplay, and youmustcreate an account. Although it can run in the background for the most part, the matter of the fact is that it is extra DRM that no one really wants, and contributes to a longer startup time.The Story- Full of clichés and it being overall boring, the story is pretty much mandatory in order to reach level 50. The movie-like cutscenes in it are neat, but if you are like me, you'll do the story just to get it out of the way. The fun seems to come after it's over with.Closing ThoughtsDespite some big flaws, I have enjoyed this game a lot, and I would say it's in my top 5 racing games now. If you can look past the cons listed above, I easily recommend this game to anyone that enjoys racing games, or is looking to try the genre in general. The game is a blast with a couple friends, especially doing the races that can take over an hour, or just going for a cruise. The Crew earns an 8/10 for me. And if The Crew 2 lives up to its hype, I don't doubt that I'll be buying it right off."
