,Recommended,241560,21403283,"Posted: 23 February, 2016",all,Ahmed el-Jaheeb,"The Crew is a very fun game, spiritual successor to Test Drive Unlimited 1 and 2. A very unique racing game. You're given some missions, money and access to a ton of cars where you can freely drive around a giant open world with a lot of variation. You have snowy area's complete with a lack of grip, the Nevada desert and the urban areas of NYC. All this while meeting a ton of players along the way which make roadtrips very fun.However, there are definite downsides. The game is pretty arcadey, steering wheel support is not that good, there's some really weird things. For example: bikes can push cars out of the way.All in all I'd still recommend the game for it is truly a unique game."
,Recommended,241560,21430339,"Posted: 24 February, 2016",all,LinkJMA,"TL;DR - I'd recommend picking it up when it goes on sale or if you know you've got friends to play it with, as the campagin is hopelessly short and there's not much endgame content without the Wild Run DLC. Still incredibly enjoyable if you like cars, exploration, or customization.-Cars. There's a lot of them, a wide variety of real life brands, and there's some pretty extensive visual customization for almost all of them.-Microtransactions exsist, but almost all of them are shortcuts that you can eventually reach in the base game, or are simply visual components.-It's always online, but I've never experienced any server difficulties.- Geography is completely boned up, but many of the cities or landscapes capture the essence of the town they smulate. Someone living in San Francisco won't recognize many streets, but it still feels like the city.- Game sometimes can seem empty. Civilian foot traffic is low in cities, and occasionally traffic is sparse.-Devlopers are still actively involved and relasing content, so that's pretty cool.The storyline is the video game equivalent of a wet piece of toast - bland, uninspiring, and so generic that you completely forget about it. There's some pretty cringey dialogue, some pretty bad voice acting, and your protagonist is an unrelatable walking cliche. Once you hit the cap of level 50, it's a short MMO-style grind to max out your car, and then it seems like you're done with the game.This is when the Wild Run DLC becomes a lfiesaver. It introduces weekly and monthly challenges against other people, inspiring you to come back again and again. It adds real end game content, and I highly recommend it."
