,Recommended,241560,14521276,"Posted: 17 February, 2015",all,Volt,"The CrewThis is a game I played briefly in Beta and really like the concept of a racing game that lets you travel across the US.  The open world environment allows you to compete in races across the US or just take off and drive anywhere you want from coast to coast without any loading screens. The freedom and choice is yours to make.  Follow the story, venture out and explore, and/or compete in challenges and races. The game feels a lot like Watchdogs if you never left the vehicle only on a larger scale with less people walking around. The vehicles handle similar to the vehicles in Watchdogs intially, but moding them greatly increases performance as you level the car.  Street, dirt, and track veriations of car modifications can be made for all different types of races as well as a large veriety of cosmetic options to customize your ride.  You will not get the sim race track feeling here as the cars are not heavily based on true physics like you would find in the Grid series.  This is definately an arcade style racing game more in line with Need for Speed that provides hours of fun!Not Just a RacerThe Crew is more than just a traditional racing game.  It is a MMO racing game.  The game is designed to play with other people by joining crews so that you can work together in missions.  Playing with others in your crew provides extra incentives such as experience and cash.  You can put skill points into your bonuses to increase rewards received from playing with your crew members as well as benefits to enhance your car such as reduced repair costs, better breaking, etc. However, the game can be played solo with just as much fun.Weak LinkageAnd here is the weak link in the design of The Crew.  People expecting a MMO will immediately notice that there is no need to join a community to play the game.  The option is there with some rewards but there is no real push to do so. There is also no voice chat built into the game to communicate with your crew members and the pop-up screen is usually hidden to get it out of the way. So even when you do choose to type to crew members, you will seldom get a response.You will find PvE and PvP races/challenges but the need for a community feels absent.  The PvP is fun and I honestly have a blast with some of the game modes.  You will not find any large raid like content here.  It would have been nice to see large cross country races pitting  multiple four man crews against crews or larger 16 plus members competing together in a large scale race against other crews or AI; but what we received was on a much smaller basis for those that want to play solo.  What you will find is a huge open world where you can see people and choose to interact with them or not.  The choice is yours to make.ProsHuge map to ExploreOpen WorldVariety of Race typesVariety of Vehicles/typesVehicle CustomizationGraphicsMMO CommunityConsPhysics are more Arcade than SimWeak MMO CommunityNo voice built in voice chatFinal ThoughtsAfter finishing the game, I still enjoy going back and creating new cars and leveling them up.  I am personally having a blast with this game and recommend it to anyone thats like racing games.   I did not do a first impressions video of this game so I have linked a few videos to give you an idea of what to expect.New Expansion UpdateThe Crew: WIldrun is a DLC expansion coming to the crew with a free overhaul to the graphics and physics engine for all as well as the DLC packed full of quests, races, new race types, vehicles, and vehicle types (monster trucks & motorcycles). It looks amazing!  I cannot wait until November to play it. If only I had a Beta key...For the story:http://steamcommunity.com/sharedfiles/filedetails/?id=351697011For vehicle modification:http://steamcommunity.com/sharedfiles/filedetails/?id=351697009For gameplay:http://steamcommunity.com/sharedfiles/filedetails/?id=394438020"
