,Recommended,241560,32838541,Posted: 26 June,all,Verbank the NEET,"It's just busy work, The lot of it.You won't get anything new from this, at the end of the day it's just your bog standard open world racing game with performance upgrades locked behind skill challenges.The driving model is simple. it's not quite an assetto corsa, and it's not even a forza. It has more in common with Grand Theft Auto 5 which is to say the driving is approachable and welcoming to all skill sets. However, due to this it is also lacking in challenge and the blatant and rubber banding in the game only serves to alienate the hardcore driver even more.Despite how large the world is you don't have very many single player races to attend to, it's especially odd considering how many real-world race tracks are in the game. Don't think this is a wasted oppertunity though, the tracks are especially innaccurate and are more like cartoons of the tracks presented rather than the actual tracks.The cars are the real stars of the show and the selection, while passable, does not showcase too many obscurities or cult classics. The car selection was more to please the crowd rather than actually shed light on cars that people have forgotten about. I mean it's fine having your R34 GT-R's and your Chevy Camaro SS's but after countless games with those cars featured surely it'd be nice to feature something else, something historical, something new, something borrowed and something blue.The story is Need For Speed Undercover crossed with the 2005 cartoon series Acceleracers crossed with Fast and the Furious. It's a world where everything revolves around street racing, especially crime. It's the dumbest thing I've ever watched in a long time where everything was conveyed so seriously. I honestly feel like all of it would've made more sense in french.It feels like it was written from the perspective of someone who doesn't really understand why people like cars but really likes the fast and furious films but doesn't speak english so they had to watch it subtitled and really didn't pay attention to the subs half the time. In addition, it's very noticable that the main story of the game is just a patchwork blanket of 'things-that-happen-that-don't-really-matter-that-we-put-in-cus-we-need-gameplay'.Everything is contrived. The entire setup for the game is contrived. Theres no setup TO the setup of the game. It's a bit of a mess. I mean, yeah, I don't expect shakespeare but I also don't expect dry oatmeal as the story to my trippe A racing game. There are NO plot threads that are interesting. There are NO characters that are interesting. They set up something and it's payoff is so flaccid I would've rather had no payoff. In parts it feels like the writer thought they were being really hard hitting with their drama but without anything to really get me invested it just made me feel embarrassed on behalf of the people who made this game.The characters really aren't characters, they're just plot devices used to justify reasons as to why you're doing a certain task at a certain time. I can tolerate it but the games serious tone just sucks the joy out of it. I was left longing for Forza Horizon's justification of: ""it's a festival"" for everything you did because that had a tiny bit of joy to it, this is just miserable.+Approachable driving model+Large map-tv movie story-forgettable characters-milquetoast car selection-rubber banding-R34 GT-R with steering wheel on the left hand of the car (WTF?!)Final scoreIt's a racing game/10"
