,Recommended,241560,13231351,"Posted: 4 December, 2014",all,=BG= Fuzzy_Rogue,"Okay here I am, two years after the game got released. And having bought the Gold edition, and now CAU with WR it wasn't the cheapest thing here. Hell I might have bough a ship in Star Citizen instead of this. But this game has given me Many hours of relaxation. If we are talking about PVP even some frustration. If you want an open world racing game, get this, but I'd wait for a sale, since it's crazy buying it for the full price with the DLC's, it's important to say that you are good to go with the standard version, altough CAU brings some sweet Police vehicles.But hey first I'll tell you what you will completely love about this game.The world, it's just so huge that I can't stop loving it. I always wanted a racing game where instead of just running around tracks, you could just set a course and go that way. And these guys finally did it. I've driven aimlessly for about 500km's (real). And then another 500 km's with set destinations (without any purpose)And another 300km's when I had to get somewhere.So that's the open world done.Racing SP - AI is weird and stupid. But it can be quite enjoyable to try and stay in the perfect line on the current track. Singleplayer racing is more used for grinding money.Racing MP - I don't like it. It's just exploiting the games arcade drive model. So instead of real driving action you are just sliding and doing unrealistic stuff all the time.The Summit - You do some stuff from time to time to increase your chance to get a vehicle for free, nothing extra.CAU pursuits - Feel extremely weird... You have two abilities, as racer and even as a cop. They slightly are slightly different from each other, but extremely OP. Just press one button each 40s to literally stop each and everys cop atempt to stop you, cop players end up just resetting to the transporter to get emp'ed again... Cops are in a huge disadvantage, if you are Dark Souls kind of player who just wants to die of frustration, suit yourself. For Racers it's a grinding quest, where occasionally you get intercepted by a cop player, and just follow two simple rules 1) head for the destination 2) Press any of your abilities when ready and cop players are nearby to ruin their day and secure yourself that you get the money to buy another car to do the same thing again to buy another car and so on.Vehicles - Another thing that I love about this game is the amount of cars. They might not represent their real life counterparts. But hey, they are not completely same cars. You get European supercars, classics, sportscars, American Muscle cars and Japanese tuners. If you have a favorite car, it is probably there.Customization is also fine, most of the time you get about 8 bumper variations, hoods. Wings, rims. Hell of a lot of colors and stickers. To make your favorite car appeal to you even more.Also I really love the added police vehicles. Nothing says security more then a cop driving 360km/h in a police Lamborghini Gallardo SVVerdict - This game is just great for wandering off just like you do for instance in Skyrim.Unfortunately you can see throughout the game that the energy to develop this game went into the wrong aspects. I personally think that Ivory Tower should've gone into the RP style of gameplay, similar to Test Drive Unlimited. They focus too much on ""your"" Crew, that is just a normal group like in WoW or any other MMORPG.But if it is in sale, and you crave for a driving game with vast open world and a variety of vehicles. I say go for it."
