,Recommended,241560,20061614,"Posted: 29 December, 2015",all,FatChickThriller,"The only reason you should buy this game, and I stress this, the ONLY reason, is if you love the idea of driving around the United States of America. The map is the selling point of this game. A gigantic condensed map of the US, Driving corner to corner it a moderately quick car, enjoying the sights and the roads, will take you about 2 hours or so. The map is just so massive and diverse, and once you get out of Detroit and Chicago, it is so ridiclously pretty. I am biased as I have travelled all over the US, so I know city they are trying to show off. They have captured the essence of each city fairly well, with perhaps an exception of Detroit, New York and Chicago, which seem very dull, likely due to the lack of crime, pedestrians and traffic. Many of the other cities look and feel pretty spot on, especially approaching Las Vegas. However, this is the only positive of the game.The car selection is limited and dissapointing. They all handle horribly. To get something remotely playable, you need to greatly fine tune the handling, otherwise it is far too vague and unresponsive.The story in The Crew is so bad, it makes any Need For Speed story worthy of an Oscar in comparion.The game is a true dissapointment in every sense of the word... except for the map. Once you have the handling fine tuned to something remotely playable, and you manage to find one car of any remote interest. Once you hit the road and just drive, this game is more enjoyable than any other sandbox driving game, Forza Horizon included. Driving around the coasts, paticularly near New Orleans, Miami and over towards Texas is a sight to see. Driving through New Mexico at night or early evening/morning is unreal."
76561198117514938,Recommended,241560,20340477,"Posted: 5 January, 2016",all,[GP]Co-Leader Chow Chow,ITSW SO ♥♥♥♥ING FUN
,Recommended,241560,20402094,"Posted: 8 January, 2016",all,Bunyan,"After about 23 hours as of this review I'd say I have enough time under my belt to write a review so here it goes (If there are any spelling errors or gramatical errors, forgive me I type pretty fast and make mistakes). And yes UPLAY is needed for the CREW (some say this is bad some don't care. I'm one of those that don't care)The crew I had many speculation's about because people had said that it wasn't an MMO or very open world, and that you had to drive up on hills to find these stations that reveal the map like in assassins creed. People also said the story is very short and not interesting at all. So firstly let me make my claim over these.Is the crew an MMO?A. No it is not, you are locked into a session of 8 people and you will never see more than that. Someone may leave the game and a new one will join in your session but that's about it. For the most part you see people here and there and maybe you drive by them or pull up and rev your engine to race, but that's it. Other than the PVP events and races you're pretty much flying solo on this one.Is the crew open world?A. YES and in a very big way. Ever since Need for Speed hot pursuit I wanted another racing game with a very open world aspect and the CREW (for me) delivers in a big way. You start out in detroit but you can drive on down to Miami and then drive to the Grand Canyon, up to Niagra Falls and down to L.A. To me, that's pretty damn awesome. Now, is The CREW a realist representation of the USA? Yes and No, Yes they have included many major cities and landmarks as well as some famous and surrounding towns but for the most part it's highways and open roads. But they have done well to add in many other key things in between such as marshes down in Miami, many farmlands in the Midwest. And a lot of the forestry seen is pretty on par with what would be in the surrounding terrain. So is it a 100% accurate rendition of the US? No, because otherwise you'd spend days to just drive down to Miami. But is it a big open world that is like the US and offers a lot of Free Driving fun? Yes, in a BIG way.Do you reveal the map with Viewpoints like in AC?A. Kind of, you have data stations which detail monuments and skill mini games found on the roads, that's pretty much it. Where the revealing of the map comes into play is when you drive on a road or in an area it starts to reveal the map where you drove. The only other kind of ""Drive and find this"" is the hidden car parts for hot rod's and that's about it.Is the story bad?A. In my opinion it's OK, it feels like Ubisoft was going for a Fast and the Furious kind of story in a sense. But the bulk of the story is cutscenes and using races to solve issues which makes the story kind of boring here and there. But I do keep guessing as to how the story will play out so it's kept my attention at least.Now I'll detail Pro's and Con's of the crewPro's-Open world-A fair selection of cars to choose from-Lots of customization for your cars-Driving and racing is fun-Driving controls are good (I use an xbox360 controller)-Many different car customization options for off road, racing, street racing, circuit racing, etc.-For a racing game it doesn't look bad, you generally focus on the roads and your car (cars look like they are a high texture though) so texture quality isn't a huge biggy, up close you can see the lower textures but like I said, you're driving and racing in 3rd person so it's not an issue.Con's-Not an MMO, an 8 player session is not an MMO, I'd prefer if anything a 32 player session or maybe 50. I think an MMO style with hundreds of people racing could become hectic.-Framrate dips in big cities with lots to load. I'm running a GTX 980 Ti and see frame rates of 20-30 FPS in larger cities, all other times I usually got around 40-50's even in forests.-Even more customization options would be good-Microtransactions to buy more money and ""CREW credits."" You don't have to do this and can easily earn your money by just playing but this micro transaction method in gaming really needs to stop. You can also pay $3(I think) for some other vehicles that can only be bought with your real money but they aren't anything special luckily.-No custom music options in-game, this is something I really wish they put it. No idea why they can't. It's not a huge issue because I can just run it in borderless windowed and run a playlist of my own stuff on the side but it's still a minor inconvenience.Overal I'd give the crew maybe a 7.5/10. It's fun and a really awesome open world driving game, I just wish more people could be in a session and framerate dips in larger cities weren't a thing."
,Recommended,241560,20538401,"Posted: 15 January, 2016",all,♥♥♥ si dojebal ♥♥♥,Tahle hra je SUPER!!!!!!
76561198022559943,Recommended,241560,20728381,"Posted: 24 January, 2016",all,Oddball,"It's good. Really good.The driving isn't the most realistic, but that doesn't matter, compared to what the game offers. The map is huge and feels so, too. There are no walls or borders within the map, if you see it, you can drive there. To the north are mountains in the south is the Mexican border. Inbetween is a nice mix of everything; salt flats, snowy mountains, woodland. Tuning is basically unlimited. You can keep your first car and race it in every event, you don't have to purchase new cars to progress. The selection of cars is good, too. I like classic muscle cars and finished the game with only two cars, a '69 Charger for everything but the Raid class, and a Camaro for raid. All other cars where just gimmicks for free drive. The cockpit view is great, it feels real and you have a good field of view. The music is nice, too. A good selection of tracks for all genres. You can also create a custom radio station with the ingame songs, picking what you like from all other stations.But not everything is good, you need to be online to play. If you disconnect, it's game over. Usually not much of an issue, unless you are within the last miles of a long 1h+ endurance race.I recommend this game to everybody who wants a good driving game with alot to do in a large world."
