,Recommended,241560,20519123,"Posted: 14 January, 2016",all,tonykuoli,"I've been playing The Crew base game for a while since November and I only came upon it after the late-2015 patch which upgraded the graphics and physics of some cars.I love the game, yes.The Crew is simply the best driving-in-an-open-world game available on the PC, and the highlight of it is the virtual continental America with a great variety of enviroments for driving enjoyment.The cities in this game does not have a living-breathing feel, yet they act as huge playgrounds for driving the somewhat limited line-up of cars available in the game. I think Manhattan in The Crew is no smaller than GTA IV's Liberty City. The mountains and seasides in The Crew, however, are truly great places to get yourself lost in. The great open Americana-esque environment with ever-changing weather and time of day indeed provide a immersive experience which is hard to be found in any other driving games.This is a game made for virtual world explorers who happen to sit in a car seat and don't really care about too much about serious racing. The Crew's missions and racing can have result varying from exciting(compete in the snowy mountain road around Salt Lake City) to very boring(it totally miss the opportunity to make NYC as racing tracks interestingly). But the overall 'road trip' feel in this game is awesome.Then there's this always-online problem. I love the idea of 'Never Driving Alone' but the real experience is having the very common 'lost connection to server' headache... An offline 'Enjoy Driving Alone' will be appreciated, really."
