76561198027672568,Recommended,241560,21908041,"Posted: 18 March, 2016",all,Mouse,"The Crew has made me question whether anything new can be added to the racing genre. Games like Gran Turismo and Burnout seem to have cornered the market in terms of innovation merely because they got there first and racing games are typically as bare bones as games go. The Crew attempts to add new features but falls short and instead you get another brown, typical racing game. Does this make it bad? No. Is it good? No. The Crew is simply here and yet theres something about driving across country in cars you can only dream of owning that adds a sense of awe and scale to an otherwise generic game.Essentially The Crew is the first racing MMO. The idea is superb, you and everyone playing are there, competing, racing, doing challenges and exploring the entire US mainland in real time but unfortunatly falls and fails nearly everywhere. PVP has no matchmaking and is simply you VS anyone who joins that particular lobby. So someone driving a level 1200 Aston Martin can compete against someone driving a level 300 Mini Cooper and you wont know who is driving what until the event is locked in and about to begin when everyone picks their car.Lastly is the ""expansion"" and I use this term loosly, called Wild Run. This adds several new Specs that largely cant be used outside of the ""summit"" which is the largely competitive monthly meet that you must qualify for weeks before hand by partaking in stunts or freedrive challenges. Now, I have no Idea what freechallenges are, no body ever accepts my challenge invites and I never get invited, so I simply have no idea what it even is.All in all, The Crew, like most recent Ubisoft games, comes across with vast ammounts of potential but never lives up to any of it. Its here, doing what it does. It looks pretty at least."
