,Recommended,241560,30037342,Posted: 19 February,all,lukulus0,"I really enjoyed ""The Crew"" and its downloadable contents, mainly for its great open world—the reproduction of the whole United States in a smaller version.Every time I play the game, I am surprised how detailed the environment and the cities really are.Although there are game objects (like houses in small towns around the world map) which do actually appear quite often, it still is fascinating how many different buildings and environmental structures (deserts, mountains, snow landscapes) there are and how it affects the playstyle, giving the player various opportunities to enjoy the game in very different ways.The car selection in the game is good, all in all. If you want great cars however, you almost have to spend real money on as The Crew's in-game currency adds up extremely slowly.The multiplayer functionalitites of the game are fine overall. However, the game's genre would be more accurate without the ""Massive"" in ""Massively Multiplayer Online Game"". Most of the players on your map are multiple kilometers/miles away from you, but when finding one, it is really fun to drive around with the other player. Also, one thing to criticize is the game's always-online ""feature"". Playing the game when the servers are offline, which happens quite frequently, is impossible. I would like it even more if there was an offline mode, making it possible to play alone and without any active online connection.Moving on to the game's story, it is basically like in any other MMO-type racing game. Without spoiling its contents: Not too interesting, but kind of okay. You get phone calls from different people, have to drive to a specific point on a map and have to clear a specific mission. That's it.Ubisoft's DLC policy for The Crew (unlike any other of this publisher's games) is now kind of fair. You get the game for a pretty low price and the two major DLC packages (Calling all Units, including Wild Run) for a decent amount as well—compared to other games, at least. This however does not include all of the car packs, which are ridiculously expensive.The two major DLCs for the game are pretty good, actually, as they add new game mechanics like bikes or even a completely new police mode.Overall, I think that The Crew is a great game to get, mainly due to its open world features. But if you're looking for a racing game that completely focuses on the racing part, you probably want to get another game.The term which would sum up what The Crew is like would probably be ""Need for Speed, but with better online features and a more interesting map""."
