76561198034574684,Not Recommended,241560,13973479,"Posted: 13 January, 2015",all,Auntie Molestia,"The CrewThe crew is a large, open world environment with lots of multiplayer aspects and huge POTENTIAL. But from there, it’s all a bit downhill. I bought it because I wanted a driving game where you could customise your car, get chased by cops, play with friends even for a nice little drive down a motorway at 200km/h.I got what I asked for, but not what I paid for. I get my custom car, which then gets pulled away from me for mission specific cars. Now, I’m in a mission with an unfamiliar car and AI designed to be perfect. I know they are. Get the perk which shows you the lines to a race mission, I almost guarantee that the AI in 1st will be perfect to that line. Have all the skill you want, if you don’t take shortcuts or have the better car, you won’t win and if that’s the case, don’t even bother going for a perfect score. I know there are people out there who are pros and know every corner, every braking point and every shortcut. I can only imagine how much time they spent and how much sass from the NPCs they got. And then there are the regular AI cars. Not the race ones, just the normal run-of-the-mill pedestrian cars. God help if you’re going for a high score and one of those come along and pull into the lane you’re in about 50m from you.♥♥♥♥♥♥happens, but not to the AI racers.Then the authorities. Hands up all those who love a good chase scene. I do, and I thought “Yeah, lots of road and different terrain, this should be good.” Oh sweet innocence. First, find a patrol car and then crash into stuff. Problem. Find one. I’d hate to believe that there are only two patrol cars in New York. Of course, if you destroy enough stuff, you might initiate a car chase, but only after ruining the front of your vehicle and giving half a city a reason to build a concrete wall as opposed to fences. Of course, you won’t get booked if you ram into all their parked cars unless a patrol car is nearby. Oh and don’t worry about pedestrians either, they’ll jump out of your way while your barrelling down the road at high speeds. You may have noticed I’ve refrained from using the word “cop”. This is because, if you find one on foot, try running him down. He’ll jump out of your way and yell obscenities at you no matter how many times you try. Won’t even call for backup.Multiplayer. Oh boy. My friend and I tried to do a multiplayer session. We attempted about three times with it saying “unable to join crew”. About to give up, we tried once more. *pop*. We’re in lobby together. Okay then, well, we’re in, let’s meet up. We did, or rather, our name tags did. Neither of us could see each other’s car, and we were poorly synced, to the point where I would ram a cop car next to my friend which would proceed to arrest me with my friend laughing because there was nothing there.Hmmm….have I missed something. Oh yes, state of the art graphics from 2011, forced music when in missions (I like my classical), handling which feels like the roads are made of ice and a story which feels like it was pulled out of the “Hat of predictable story lines” with more plot holes in it than the Brony Clopper fandom."
