,Recommended,241560,13243290,"Posted: 5 December, 2014",all,Byr,"ThinkNeed for Speed: Most Wantedcombined withFuel. ThinkTest Drive Unlimitedcombined withDriver: San Francisco. ThinkNeed for Speed: Worldcombined withBurnout Paradise. Think…ehh, you get the point. If any of the games I’ve listed so far tickle your fancy, or even combinations of them, thenThe Crewmight be for you.The game has its quirks and its rough patches, but it is generally an alright game. The story is bland, the graphics could be a smidge better, the car handling takes time to get used to, and the claim that it’s an MMO is kind of false. I’m not saying the graphics are bad, they just have their moments of making me say “that could look better.”The car handling, at least for a 'keyboard racer,' works but feels somewhat odd. I've yet to tryThe Crewwith a controller or steering wheel. At times I feel like I'm not in complete control of the car. Playing with all the assists off just made the game harder, not so much more enjoyable. I now play with all assists on because I'm already tapping the left and right arrow keys twenty times per second. Vehicle collision bugs me. Sometimes you'll tap a wall or car and bounce off unharmed. Other times you'll nudge the same entity and do a full 180 and come to a screeching halt. The AI of the other racers and police are painfully scripted. Cops have near infinite acceleration and top speed at times. Opponent racers haul♥♥♥♥♥off the line leaving you in the dust for a bit. And towards the end of a race, the AI ""gets tired"" and basically coasts for the remainder of the race, allowing you to finish first almost every time.CallingThe Crewan MMO is incorrect. The roads aren’t full of other players. In fact, they’re almost completely void of other players.The Crewonly ever boasts 8 players on the same map at once. If you’ve played other multiplayer racing games, I’m sure you’re used to the whole “drop-in, drop-out” system. Regardless, for most of the time I’ve playedThe Crew, I’ve generally been either completely alone in my own world or only paired with 1 or 2 other players. Players can invite others to do missions with them, but I’ve only ever received a handful of invites. It seems that withThe Crewyou either have friends to drive with or you don’t. But then again, I didn't buy it to mindlessly hang out with other players and talk smack about their iridescent paint jobs.But besides this, I find myself compelled to keep playing.The Crewcombines open-world racing with some RPG elements. Grinding XP, car parts, and money is there. Oh, and numbers.So many numbers.The sheer amount of digits littering your screen upon completion of a challenge, race, or mission is a bit daunting. But as you do missions, you’ll level up your general level, as well as your car’s level.Thus, more numbers.Needless to say, I likeThe Crew. I’m sure not everyone will enjoy it. It definitely sets itself apart from other racing games, at least a little. I’m a fan of the customization, the leveling, the open-world, and the numbers (oh baby the numbers). It’s a game to keep an eye on to see where it goes, or maybe even what games spawn because of it and its ancestors. And if you still have a vendetta againstUbisoftafter their previous releases,as in 99% of the people reading this,just know that this game actually works...though you will have to suffer because of the UPlay integration."
