76561197972609948,Recommended,241560,11916036,"Posted: 29 August, 2014",all,Betelgeuse,"Pinged off into space, got an achievement for reaching 250 miles per hour for the first time.I enjoyed my time playing the beta.  The map is really big.  Its a stylized version of the United States and it takes a good while to drive from one side to the other.  I tried to have cops chase me from one end of the country to the other, but the waypoint line kept dissapearing.  Then I would just get lost.  Wouldn't be a terrible idea to add in compass or some road signs.  You don't have to stick to the roads though, which really increases the area of your playground.The dirt specced cars handle just as well offroad as they do on pavement, with the sacrifice of speed.  They let you try out the other specs in missions, and they seem pretty fun too.  Performance, Raid and Circuit all have their different specialties as you would expect, though you start with a fullstock car that is pretty slow and handles poorly.  You get your street spec shortly after which will improve incrementally.Car handling is good.  As you level up and gain better parts from missions and skill tests, the way your car handles will change drastically.  They capped the beta at level 10, and I have mostly level 10 gold parts.  The car handles completely different.  It sticks to the road a lot better and feels an awful lot like the Need for Speed series.When you open the map, your car just sits in the middle of the road.  When I first started the game, I got my crappy fullstock car and did what anyone else would do.  I set a waypoint and put the hammer down.  What I didn't realize at the time was, that other people were also in the process of doing the same thing.  They had moved ahead and were now sitting dead in the road checking their map.  All the npc cars kind of clumped up around them as they slowed down to go around.   Fullstock cars don't really brake or turn well.  They don't happen to stick to the road as you would like them to.  What they do well, is turn into a ballistic missile when you try to evade these little clumps.  I'm sorry to the 5 or so people I smashed into.That being said, there isn't much of a penalty for causing gigantic accidents.  There also isn't much in the way of reactions.  Cars get dented up, and you get a short little slowed down cutscene of your car smashing into the other car (or tree, etc).  You loose a little health permanently (until you repair) and the rest regenerates.  Sometimes the police get on you because of this.  With a lower level car, it was challenging to get away from the police, but with my 213 street car, it can be more difficult to keep from out running them.  I expect the difficulty will be ramped up by release with more police variation.  They will do a few neat things like try to box you in and stop you.  They'll try to ram and pit you, but for the most part they're kinda dumb.The cars sound great and the graphics are really well done.  Small glich; the radio plays really low for me.  Sounds like I'm outside the car listening to the music, but the mustang sounds like a guess a mustang would.  There is a good sense of scale and size to the city when you're in it.  The buildings are tall and the streets are pretty wide.  Las Vegas has pretty lights and is in the middle of a desert.  Looks incredible as your driving up to it at night.  Miami is nice, and Washington D.C. is a short hop from New York.  It looks like they could potentially add in other maps as well.I want them to have better filters for the map, so you can see other people better, and isolate which missions and skills will give you upgrades.  I saw people, but not as many as I expected.  There were definately a lot of people playing, but it seemed to split people up into server shards.  I really hope they allow more people onto the same session at release.This game really has a lot of potential.  As it is, its a really fun experience.  I enjoyed my time with the game.  Played with a GTX 660; i5 4670k 3.4Ghz Quad Core, 16 GB Ram and a  500GB solid state drive.  Ran very smooth on ultra 1080p fullscreen with an occasional hard stutter that would recover after a few seconds.  They only happened about once an hour or so.  I expect graphics card drivers to fix this, because the game seemed to be optimized for my rig specifically.  I read others have had some problems, as it does require a fairly sturdy computer."
