76561198170403889,Not Recommended,241560,29341975,Posted: 18 January,all,Tiozão do Pavê,"Free-roaming is no novelty - games like Grand Theft Auto and Driver have been doing this for almost two decades, and titles like Need For Speed Underground 2, Shutokou Battle and Burnout Paradise, among others, have tried to apply such gameplay concept to racing games, with mixed results - but free-roaming through an entire country (or at least a scaled-down version thereof) is a whole new idea. And The Crew manages to offer just that - storming through highways on a fast car, looking for new events and maybe some interesting sights. The important question (which shall be answered in this review) is: does it really work?Superficially, The Crew offers some really impressive content: a giant map for the player to explore to one's heart's content, a could-have-been-better-but-not-bad car list, plenty of tuning options (not as complete as what was offered by Need For Speed Underground some fourteen years ago, though), variable weather and time of the day; those things can easily elicit the player's attention (and, as a matter of fact, they really got my attention for a first moment) and may be really satisfying if expectations are kept somewhat low of if the player just wants some casual driving fun. Because, once the initial appeal is gone and after putting some hours delving into the game, some players may notice that The Crew offers *just* that - a game that is best played as a casual experience, even though it tries hard to take itself seriously.Driving through the streets, avenues and highways of the USA, perhaps the most appealing part of the game, becomes boring too quickly; the game map is astonishingly huge, and yet it is underused, making speeding through a sparsely populated road just as fun as a prolonged family trip. Car handling just does not feel right; cars feel weightless, the brakes work a little too well to be realistic (even in accordance to a ""simcade"" game's standards), and any sharper turn, however subtle, puts your car in a powerslide. It reminds me a little bit of the Playstation's port of San Francisco Rush, with some elements borrowed from Sega's Outrun 2 (a game which is sadly missing on Steam). There are also some bugs (my car became completely unresponsive for no apparent reason once, and sometimes the game just refuses itself to launch, even though my computer exceeds the minimum requirements), though I believe Ubisoft may be ironing out the most serious offenders. The events scattered though the map are also nothing to write home about and may get old pretty quick, and the dialogues and cutscenes are kinda forgettable (the Japanese voiceovers, however, are excellent). The always-online requirement is really irritating and sometimes can ruin the experience (just try to imagine yourself riding through a laggy and unstable virtual road).The Crew has a brighter side, however. Graphics are gorgeous, the cars are nicely modeled, speacial effects are top-notch and the landscapes and cities are believable (even though they're a bit underpopulated and somewhat lifeless and bland). Sound is also really good, with realistic-sounding engines, tires screeching and crashes. And I really encourage the players to stop by a residential area and watch the virtual denizens chat for a while; it really adds a little bit of life to the game (and I also encourage you to change the audio language to Japanese).Does The Crew satisfy the premise of bringing a whole virtual country for virtual drivers to race around and be a bit more useful than a bunch of joyriders? Well... no. The abovementioned flaws may be off-putting for players looking for a more serious challenge and rewarding gameplay, and the lag issues and questionable car control can even anger consumers looking for an arcade-y game to kill some time which would be best spent on other activities. However, The Crew is a game which rewards patience and persistence (I mean, A LOT of patience and persistence), even if such reward isn't that great.It is an interesting game, in the end. But it could have been more, it could have been much more. - 6,5/10"
