76561198217688739,Not Recommended,241560,33256190,Posted: 4 July,all,Goldenhawk5219,"I played this game on the PS4 for 100+ hours so don't be fooled by my playtime hours of this game from Steam. It's really dissapointing that even with it being the same online-only game and spent so much time on the PS4 version and so much progress, that I can't transfer my save to PC. So now I have to start ALL OVER again.--SHORT VERSION--PROS:- Huge map- Good amount of car custimization- Fun multiplayer with good variety of game modes- Neat car showrooms with car testing before buying- Free-cam mode for making cool looking screenshots- cloud-savingCONS:- Terrible, disjointed, and condensed copy-paste map of the U.S.- Graphics look terrible at times with low-poly textures.- Clunky vehicle physics- Very grindy part leveling- Unrealistic vehicle topspeeds- Frustratingly slow money earning that can take hours upon hours of racing- Special multiplayer events with exclusive rewards that are not at-your-own leisure and expire within real-world times, mimicking time-based mobile games.- Can't transfer saves from platform to platform.- Third party app required to play on PC.--DETAILED VERSION--PROS:- Huge map that is bigger than Test Drive Unlimited's Hawaii, 1:1 scaled map and Test Drive Unlimited 2's Ibiza, 1:1-scaled map combined with different veriations of environments. Cool landmarks to visit.- Good bit amount of vehicle custimization options and fun to watch a standard street car turn into a monster truck or an offroad vehicle.- Fun multiplayer competition with different gamemodes and co-op missions.- Neat car showroom visuals that let you look at each vehicle by opening and closing doors, honking the horn, looking at the inside of the car from first person, freely moving the orbit-camera and test driving any vehicle before purchasing.- Free-cam mode with many options that lets you move the camera around freely and take awesome screenshots for showing off to friends and uploading.- Progress loss is impossible with your saves constantly being uploaded to the serversCONS:- Instead of having a really cool fictional map to drive around and explore in, the developers decided to design this wierd condensed, disfigured map of the USA. It gets really akward when driving from like New York City to Chicago in 10 minutes and gets really comedic at times watching how small and close together cities, towns and highway systems are. Residential areas especially look VERY close together and look extremely artificial. Parking lots and back alley streets look hilariously disjointed and have small pillars installed with tall invisible walls to keep you from exploring and discovering more of how terrible they look. Also the cities and towns in this game look about the same and only have a few unique land features and structures such as monuments but that's about it. Driving around in these cities and towns are also very limited when it comes to freedom because just about every shopping plaza, town home, and generic copy-paste business building and strips have these wierd looking short shouldn't-be-there pillars with invisible walls that keep you from driving up steps and their alleyways that totally look like you should be able to drive up on. Even most of the ramps in this game that you should obviously be able to drive up on have these invisible walls that even keep monster trucks out. Hell even most of the parks in the cities and towns in this game are strangely off limits! As badly put together the map looks, alot of the areas literally look like a custom map you would make in a Far Cry game trying to mimic a big city in real life. It just doesn't look right AT ALL. All this just so the developers can brag at E3 saying that the ""Whole USA map is at your hands to explore"". WTF.- Even after the Wild Run update that gave the game a graphics and color boost, it still looks really terrible at times, especially in the cities. Player vehicles and country environments can look very screenshot-pretty, but when it comes to generic civilian cars, pedestrians, buildings, and landmarks, it reminded me of when I played those Need for Speed games in the mid 2000's. Low-polygon textures and absolutely low details made me wonder what the hell the developers were thinking when it came to quantity over quality.- Clunky car physics that are wierder than Midnight Club L.A.'s. Going offroad and want to climb a rock with your monster truck or drive over a car? Good luck with that. Hitting a wall at 200 MPH barely scratches the front end of your car but driving into or through small bushes and brush absolutely destroy your car. Your car slowly ""heals"" over time, so it becomes laughable watching your car's damaged body artificially correct itself and transform as if nothing ever happened as your driving.- Extemely grindy trying to get higher level car parts. And I mean it is soo grindy, it will drive you up the walls if not literally. It will feel like you are playing a mobile game like NFS No Limits when it comes to car progression.- Very unrealistic and unfair top speed when you have just about all of the highest level parts for your cars because whether you have the slowest or fastest cars in the game, they will all have THE SAME top speeds and acceleration which makes ABSOLUTELY NO SENSE. No point of spending 700,000+ credits that took 50+ hours for you to get when you can spend 16,000 on a slow car that will have the same power as that Ferarri when you have all the highest level parts.- Takes a VERY LONG time to get money in this game if you don't want to spend real money for in-game credits, hence the microtransactions they throw at you all the time. Even with money-earning perks maxed out and exploits you may find to get more money quicker, It WILL STILL take you LOTS and LOTS of racing just to get a decent amount to buy a Mustang and that's not counting custimization parts and such.- Real-time multiplayer events that require you to not have a life because they are in-sync with real world time that expire after a certain day or time just like a mobile game does. Not really an at-your-own leisure friendly game when it comes to engaging in special higher-reward events with exclusive car rewards and parts. Really dissapointing if you have a job and can't make it when you come home and find out that you missed an event with that exclusive car you wanted to win and will never get.- Can't transfer saves from platform to platform, despite being able to link your Xbox Live Account and PSN to your Ubisoft account which is useless to do with this game. Each platform has its own servers for online which can be frustrating if transfering.- Required to have a seperate third-party app, UPlay installed and running on your computer which can take up valuable hardware. So now not only do you have shortcut keys for and overlay of Steam running in the background while playing The Crew, you ALSO have an overlay and shortcut keys for UPlay running in the background as well while playing.*This game is OK. It can be really fun at times with HUGE jumps to make, driving 300 MPH+ in drag car builds, playing around with friends and showing off each other's vehicle builds and paint designs, going into free-cam mode and taking awesome screenshots, but the negatives feel like they just totally outweigh the positives for me. Especially with games that I have that are far more interesting and fun to play than this one.** When I had this game for PS4, I really liked it because it was kind of an alternative to Forza Horizon because I didn't have an Xbox One nor gaming PC at the time. I didn't have college and had alot of fun playing with friends. Now that I have a gaming PC and have college, I would rather play Forza Horizon 3, which has WAAAY more cars, more custimization options and parts, more beautiful graphics with better optimization for PC and overall just much more enjoyable to play than this game. I would rate this game a 2/5 for PC."
