76561198073511721,Recommended,241560,17146371,"Posted: 20 July, 2015",all,LolaAnderson83,"This is one of those times where Steam really needs a ""neutral"" option. I've only just started this game and so far I find it enjoyable enough but I can completely understand why people don't like it.First, let's deal with the elephant in the room: microtransactions in a $60 game, DLC is overpriced for what you get, DRM in the form of vague and unnecessary MMO-elements, and Uplay is a thing. Basically, Ubisoft is Ubisoft and ♥♥♥♥ Ubisoft.How about some positives? The world is enormous and quite beatiful too. I can't remember where I read this but I saw that someone did a road trip from NYC to LA and it took 39 minutes, averaging 150 MPH, to give you a sense of scale. There's plenty of missions and things to do, tons of hours of gameplay if you're willing to invest the time. Car customisation is fairly extensive. You have to unlock most of the parts but there are plenty as areas that can be customised, including the interior, which is something I haven't come across in other racing/car games.And now for the negatives. As you probably expect, the story is rubbish: you avenge the death of a character you've barely met as a character you won't care about. Hmm, now where have I seen this before? Oh, that's right, every other Ubisoft game of 2014! You play as Alex, a former streetracer who is working with police to takedown an illegal street racing/gun smuggling/drug sumggling gang. Like his Watch Dogs counterpart Aiden, he has all the personality of a wet napkin and is completely forgettable. And he also looks like Gordon Freeman's idiot cousin. The car list has some nice selections but it is short, only about 50 cars. The cars themselves have terrible physics that are neither realistic nor particularly fun. They feel very heavy but have little grip, and all seem to snap-oversteer at unusual times with bad understeer the rest of the time; adjusting steering sensitivity hasn't changed this. Spins that would easily be saveable with the throttle and countersteer in other games with proper physics are impossible to save here. I've only played with a 360 controller so far but I'll try my racing wheel at some point to see how that goes. Side quests (mostly small challenges scattered throughough the world) unlock new performance parts but are very repetitive and mostly ""meh"" anyway.So why do I recommend this game? Personally, I get a lot of enjoyment from just cruising around the world, discovering landmarks and locations along the way. That factor alone has actually the purchase for me, and the fact I got it on sale made the deal much better. Overall, while I haven't played the most recent games in the series, The Crew feels on par with most of the Need For Speed games I've played: not much in the way of a good narrative but a decent car game, if you're into that sort of thing. If you own an Xbox One (I don't but often use my friend's), I'd recommend picking up Forza Horizon 2 instead; it's a substantially better game on the whole. If you don't, you could do worse than this. The reason I enjoy it is very likely in the minority but to each his/her own. There is a free 2 hour demo, so download that and see what you think."
