,Recommended,241560,13809564,"Posted: 3 January, 2015",all,TheWaxwingSlain,"The Crew is one spectacular game.   I was a bit worried when I saw reviews saying the racing wasn't that good, but after 290 hours in the game (and still playing), I can say the racing is a complete blast.  The thing is, people who are used to NFS racing where you never have to touch the brakes might dislike the handling - at first.  But after you tune your car up to maybe  600 you start to see the wisdom in the approach The Crew takes.  Things tighten up.  If you want to drift, you can drift your butt off, but holding the best racing line is better.The classes of car work very well.  Raid cars are incredibly fun, whether climing mountain ranges in the Montana Rockies or blasting through New Mexico canyons.  My favorite is crashing through the Everglades on a race to East Texas.And that leads me to what makes this game unlike any other, ever:  The amazing scope of the location.  You can drive from Maine to the Baja without seeing a single loading screen.  You want to be part of a faction mission that will take over an hour?  It's there.  The locations are simply amazing.  Exploration behind the wheel is simply unreal.  And there's nowhere you can't go.  The only ""walls"" are the borders and coastlines of the United States.  All I can do is pray for The Crew2: Europe.The Crew multiplayer is very well done and getting better.  Factions, co-op and just exploring with your crew is a ton of fun and I can see putting another few hundred hours into the game.The only complaint I have about The Crew is the soundtrack.  They really should have spent a few bucks and gotten some good songs to go with the missions.  One thing I've liked about NFS games (and of course Burnout Paradise) is the selection of songs, some familiar, some new.  There's nothing memorable at all about the song choices in The Crew.  So, what I do is load up Spotify in the background and start up a playlist of a couple of thousand songs I've picked over the years for racing games like this. It reminds me of my early days when I got my first car and there was nothing better than driving around blasting the radio and  jamming out when a great song came on.  The only thing missing today is the roach in the ashtray.This is very close to my favorite game of 2014.  In a year with some pretty impressive games, The Crew stands out for me.  I love this game."
